g.text: Why do we need Vector Database?

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: SQL and NoSQL databases are designed to find exact matches based on known

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: values, while vector databases are designed to find similar items based on

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: The reason a full scan is slow is because it's perfect.

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: It calculates the distance to every single point and

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: guarantees it finds the absolute closest one.

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: This is called Exact Nearest Neighbor (ENN) search.

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji
Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Approximate nearest neighbor (ANN) is an algorithm that finds a data

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: point in a data set that's very close to the given query point,

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: but not necessarily the absolute closest one.

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji
Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji
Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: It sacrifices a tiny amount of accuracy (it might return 9 of the top 10, plus the 11th)

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: for a massive gain in speed (often orders of magnitude faster).

g.text: Find the "Centers": The database first looks at all of your million vectors

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: and uses an algorithm (like k-means clustering) to find, let's say,

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 100 "center points" or centroids. Each centroid is itself a vector that

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: represents the average of a region in your data. Think of these as the

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: signs for the sections in our library: "Fiction," "Science," etc.

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji
Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Assign to Clusters: The database then goes through every single one of

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: your million vectors and figures out which of the 100 centroids it's closest

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: to. It then puts a "pointer" to that vector into a list for that centroid.

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji
Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji
Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Now you come with your query vector for "light blue summer shirt."

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Find the Closest Section(s): The database does NOT compare your

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: query to all one million vectors. Instead, it just compares it to the

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: 100 centroids. This is super fast. It finds that your query is closest

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji
Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji
Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Search Only Within That Section: Now, the database knows your best

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: matches are probably in the list for Centroid #42.

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: So it only searches through the 10,000 vectors in that one cluster.

g.text: First Split: We pick a dimension (e.g., the x-axis) and find the middle point (the median).

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: We draw a vertical line there. All points to the left go into the "left" branch of our tree,

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: Approach 4: The Compression Method (Product Quantization - PQ)

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: A single vector using 1536 dimensions of 32-bit floating-point numbers

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: takes up 1536 * 4 bytes = 6,144 bytes. If you have a billion vectors,

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: that's 6.1 Terabytes of RAM! That's incredibly expensive.

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji

g.text: It chops the big vector into smaller segments. For example,

text.font-family: Excalifont, Xiaolai, sans-serif, Segoe UI Emoji
